Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely to occur, because at the end of the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many aspects, particularly in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the origin of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Then, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed and when no credit is available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without precursors.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this scenario were to repeat itself, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could signal excessive regulations, state takeover, and disengagement with globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a crisis of the sovereign debts of the advanced countries.
Financial and economic imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
The imbalances and undetected systemic risks make fiscal policies that seem prudent not actually prudent.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenses were largely determined by a real estate bubble linked to very high indebtedness.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also trigger a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative impact on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is probably a typical example of this.
As a last resort, the only way out is to reset the value of the liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger such sequential imbalances in a cascade, sovereign states must be vigilant to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking rapid corrective measures.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits to the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms, will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will by no means solve the problems of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and predicting instability.
In addition to new legislative frameworks, a full-fledged system of surveillance of systemic risks is necessary.
However, certain leading politicians and analysts estimate that such a system, aiming to identify and contain systemic risks, is futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a constantly evolving global financial system make risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than what we thought necessary just three years ago.
In the domain of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists in rejecting a true proposition and the other is to accept a false proposition.
Let us call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be asked in these terms: in the context of risk detection and response to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the probable highest cost?
The opponents of prudent surveillance of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable predictive sign of potential growing instability.
Chercher un tel signe is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantaneously.
However, this position appears to be fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, certain analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
We must however admit that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the point of rupture.
They were, however, undeniable signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This point of view implies that AQF has a probable higher cost than RQV, because there are many positive false elements and/or that the remedy is worse than the disease.
No doubt there are costs associated with the AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the overall negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper trend at work.
Whether it is in business or investments, choices are constantly made in conditions of uncertainty and frequent errors occur.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be the opposite, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless having good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at least debatable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
However, we should at least try the experience, and give the responsibility to a new institution, or an existing one, which has access to relevant information, which has analytical skills both at the financial and macroeconomic levels, and which is relatively immune to conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, increasing thereby the ability of the financial system to regulate itself.
